\i0\b0  - the 
\b clone 1
\b0  button will copy the value in the first step to all other steps.\
A 
\b random velocity
\b0  can also be set for each note. This is useful for so-called "humanisation" of  of patterns to make them sound less machine-like.\
The 
\b step/note lengths
\b0  button displays the length in beats of each step/note as a fraction: X over Y.  So for example 1 over 2 would be a step length of 1/2 or 0.5 beats. Or 3 over 4 would be a step length of 3/4 or 0.75 beats. A checkbox shows various presets - select a preset to set all step & note lengths to the preset value. \
The 
\b probability
\b0  button displays the probablity of each step playing.\
A probabililty of 100 would mean that the step would always be played.\
A probabililty of 33 would mean that the step would be played 33 percent of the time - on average only every 3rd time the sequence is played.  This is useful for creating sequences that change every cycle, with some steps playing every time, and others only sometimes.\
The 
\b delay
\b0  button displays the delay amount of each step.  A step can be delayed by up to 50% of the step time. \
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\ql\qnatural

\b \cf0 random delay
\b0  adds a random delay to each step. This is useful for so-called "humanisation" of the timing of patterns to make them sound less machine-like.\
Delay can also be used to make a swung rhythm by delaying every second step.\

\b random octave
\b0  - if this is not zero, the note will be transposed by a random no of octaves between 0 and that value. For example a value of 2 will mean every time that step is played, it could be transposed by 0, 1, or 2 octaves.\
The random octave is set every time a step is played. Negative values are allowed which will transpose downwards to lower octaves.\

\b control 1/2/3
\b0  - these controls are not used for creating notes, but they are output as control signals at the same time as notes are played in each step.\
